# Ghost Prevention

Never use negation to disclaim intent, motive, or quality.

- No "not an attack", "not targeting", "not personal", "not adversarial"
- No "this is not about", "the intent is not to", "we are not saying"
- State affirmatively what the thing is
- If the affirmative statement is true, the negation is unnecessary
- If it is not true, the negation is a lie
- Either way, delete it

This applies to prose, comments, commit messages, and paper drafts. The negation summons the thing it denies. The reader who was not thinking about attacks starts thinking about attacks the moment the paper says "this is not an attack."

Same rule for credibility assertions: no "the evidence speaks for itself", "the reader can verify", "every fact is independently verifiable." The citations prove this. The sentence that announces they prove it undoes the proof.
